00:05:14.520 --> 00:05:18.760
these issues that I'm discussing in this series.

00:05:18.760 --> 00:05:23.120
Okay, so today we're going to talk&nbsp;
about rational polynomial sequences,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:23.120 --> 00:05:32.120
or maybe rational polyon sequences for short.&nbsp;
I'm going to follow a, by now, hopefully familiar&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:32.120 --> 00:05:41.400
framework. We started off with this course talking&nbsp;
about natural numbers, integers, fractions,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:41.400 --> 00:05:48.160
and working our way to rational numbers. Natural&nbsp;
numbers like this: integers were defined in terms&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:48.160 --> 00:05:55.760
of pairs of natural numbers—so, 2 less 3, that&nbsp;
was the way we introduced what we now call minus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:55.760 --> 00:06:03.320
one. We talked about fractions like 1/7, also&nbsp;
built from natural numbers, and then sort of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:03.320 --> 00:06:10.200
putting these two things together—integers over&nbsp;
integers making rational numbers—and they are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:10.200 --> 00:06:17.960
the sort of prime objects for doing arithmetic&nbsp;
in everyday life, the rational number field.

00:06:17.960 --> 00:06:23.240
Then, later, when we started introducing algebra,&nbsp;
we went up a level of sophistication and started&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:23.240 --> 00:06:30.640
talking about polynomials, or as we preferred,&nbsp;
poly numbers. Analogous to this, we had a sort&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:30.640 --> 00:06:38.560
of compatible structure of natural number poly&nbsp;
numbers, integral poly numbers, fractional poly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:38.560 --> 00:06:48.160
numbers, and rational poly numbers. Here's&nbsp;
a typical natural polynomial, and then&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:48.160 --> 00:06:53.640
taking differences of them yields integral poly&nbsp;
numbers. That's one way of introducing integral&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:53.640 --> 00:06:59.000
poly numbers. Another way is just to consider poly&nbsp;
numbers with integer coefficients, which amounts&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:07.480
to roughly the same thing. We can take ratios&nbsp;
of them to create fractional poly numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:07.480 --> 00:07:15.000
and if we do that with integer poly numbers,&nbsp;
then we get the field of rational poly numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:21.400
which is second in importance in mathematics&nbsp;
only to the field of rational numbers.

00:07:21.400 --> 00:07:25.800
So, rational numbers and rational poly&nbsp;
numbers—these are fields that support&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:25.800 --> 00:07:33.200
our four fundamental operations: addition,&nbsp;
subtraction, multiplication, and division,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:33.200 --> 00:07:39.800
with just a little bit of a problem—we're&nbsp;
not allowed to divide by zero. Otherwise,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:39.800 --> 00:07:48.520
there's a kind of uniformity and a completeness&nbsp;
in these kinds of arithmetic domains.

00:07:48.520 --> 00:07:55.040
Okay, so having understood this framework,&nbsp;
we're going to now go up a level to considering&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:55.040 --> 00:08:01.960
sequences, or on sequences, built up from&nbsp;
the basic, similar framework. We're mostly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:01.960 --> 00:08:10.240
interested today in these rational poly numbers&nbsp;
and extending them to on sequences. So, let's have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:10.240 --> 00:08:17.480
a reminder of what these objects are like and how&nbsp;
we do arithmetic with rational poly numbers. Now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:17.480 --> 00:08:22.840
in modern mathematics, these objects are&nbsp;
often called rational functions, which is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:22.840 --> 00:08:28.360
unfortunate terminology. The term "rational&nbsp;
poly numbers" or "rational polynomials" is,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:28.360 --> 00:08:34.240
I think, superior notation and more&nbsp;
properly captures what we're doing.

00:08:34.240 --> 00:08:43.360
So, I remind you that a rational poly number&nbsp;
is a formal ratio of two integral poly numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:43.360 --> 00:08:50.640
and there is an important notion of&nbsp;
equality: that P/Q = R/S precisely&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:50.640 --> 00:08:59.160
when PS = RQ. These four are all integral&nbsp;
poly numbers, so you can think of them as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:59.160 --> 00:09:07.600
polynomials with coefficients which&nbsp;
are integers—polynomials in alpha.

00:09:07.600 --> 00:09:15.160
For example, here is a rational polynomial, and&nbsp;
we'll write the fraction not with a slant like&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:15.160 --> 00:09:21.440
this but rather with a horizontal bar because it's&nbsp;
just easier to write. So, this one here, 1 - Alpha&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:21.440 --> 00:09:29.240
over 2 + Alpha squared, that's the same as Alpha -&nbsp;
Alpha squared over 2 Alpha + Alpha cubed. And why&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:29.240 --> 00:09:34.520
is that? It's because if you multiply 1 - Alpha&nbsp;
by this, it's the same as what you get when you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:34.520 --> 00:09:41.760
multiply this by Alpha - Alpha squared. And we can&nbsp;
see that in another way by just realizing that to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:41.760 --> 00:09:50.840
go from here to here, we've multiplied the top and&nbsp;
the bottom by the same poly number, namely Alpha.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:50.840 --> 00:09:55.600
So, to go from here to here, we've multiplied by&nbsp;
Alpha; to go from here to here, we've multiplied&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:55.600 --> 00:10:02.920
by Alpha. That has the effect of making sure&nbsp;
that this kind of equality is maintained. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:02.920 --> 00:10:07.800
these two rational poly numbers may look&nbsp;
different, but they are actually officially&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:07.800 --> 00:10:16.680
exactly the same objects for us. It's going to be&nbsp;
a basic but important point in today's lecture.

00:10:16.680 --> 00:10:23.840
Okay, and we can do arithmetic with these things.&nbsp;
So, for example, if we want to add this rational&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:23.840 --> 00:10:30.160
poly number and this one, well, then what we do&nbsp;
is we take this times this plus this times this,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:30.160 --> 00:10:37.080
all over this times this, just exactly&nbsp;
the same way we add fractions. Of course,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:37.080 --> 00:10:45.080
there's simplification here necessary to&nbsp;
get it in standard form, top and bottom. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:45.080 --> 00:10:49.840
of course, arithmetic with fractions,&nbsp;
with ordinary rational numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:49.840 --> 00:10:58.640
is a necessary preliminary to doing algebra with&nbsp;
these rational poly numbers. We can multiply two&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:58.640 --> 00:11:04.120
of them, in which case we just multiply the&nbsp;
numerators and multiply the denominators,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:04.120 --> 00:11:09.360
and we can also divide one by the other,&nbsp;
which amounts to multiplying this one by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:09.360 --> 00:11:16.000
the reciprocal of this one—what you get when&nbsp;
you interchange the numerator and denominator.

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:23.200
So, I hope we're all comfortable with&nbsp;
the arithmetic or the algebra of rational&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:23.200 --> 00:11:28.520
poly numbers. And let's just make sure that&nbsp;
we're all on the same level here—that we all&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:28.520 --> 00:11:37.680
appreciate that these rational poly numbers are&nbsp;
not functions. Okay, so they are not functions,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:37.680 --> 00:11:43.880
first of all, because we have not got a&nbsp;
comprehensive definition of what a function&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:43.880 --> 00:11:53.160
is—that's actually a very problematic issue. For&nbsp;
example, when we write down something like this,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:53.160 --> 00:12:02.520
T = 4 - Alpha + Alpha^5 + 7 Alpha squared, that&nbsp;
is not a function. It is simply an expression&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:02.520 --> 00:12:10.120
that we write down in terms of Alphas. So, the&nbsp;
expression itself lives above any particular&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:10.120 --> 00:12:16.800
interpretation of it. Someone can come along and&nbsp;
say, "Oh, well, that looks like a function from&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:16.800 --> 00:12:22.000
the rational numbers to the rational numbers,"&nbsp;
and someone else can come along and say, "Oh no,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:28.160
that looks like a sequence—we input a natural&nbsp;
number and get out a rational number." Someone&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:28.160 --> 00:12:34.160
else might say, "No, no, that's a function from&nbsp;
the complex numbers to the complex numbers." There&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:34.160 --> 00:12:41.520
might be lots of other possible interpretations&nbsp;
of this, but for us, the object itself is just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:41.520 --> 00:12:51.520
the expression. We do not need to specify a&nbsp;
particular interpretation of the expression.

00:12:51.520 --> 00:12:57.200
Okay, so earlier in this series, I gave&nbsp;
an entire lecture on this issue of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:57.200 --> 00:13:01.640
difference between object-oriented&nbsp;
mathematics and expression-oriented&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:01.640 --> 00:13:13.160
mathematics, and you will know that I encourage an&nbsp;
expression-oriented approach to mathematical work.

00:13:13.160 --> 00:13:18.120
Okay, there's another important notion that we&nbsp;
need to consider, and that's the evaluation of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:18.120 --> 00:13:23.520
rational poly numbers. So, for example, if we&nbsp;
stick with this one here—this T, it's a rational&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:23.520 --> 00:13:31.880
poly number—what is T of 1? Well, T of 1 is what&nbsp;
you get when you replace the alpha with the number&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:31.880 --> 00:13:45.160
1. So, 4 - 1 + 1/5 is 1 over 5 + 7 * 1 squared,&nbsp;
for a total of 4 over 12, which is a rational&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:45.160 --> 00:13:54.240
number, also equal to 1/3. Another example: we&nbsp;
could also plug in an integer, say minus 2, put&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:54.240 --> 00:14:10.720
Alpha equal to -2. We get 4 + 2 + (-2)^5, which&nbsp;
is -32, over 5 + 7 * 4, 28, giving us -26 over 33.

00:14:10.720 --> 00:14:16.560
So, in general, the rule is that if we have&nbsp;
a rational polynomial which is A over B,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:16.560 --> 00:14:24.800
where A and B are integral poly numbers, and&nbsp;
if, say, K is an integer, then P of K is,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:24.800 --> 00:14:33.680
by definition, the rational number A of K over B&nbsp;
of K. So, we have a well-defined notion of what it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:33.680 --> 00:14:41.040
means to evaluate a poly number at an integer, and&nbsp;
we're evaluating two poly numbers and taking the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:41.040 --> 00:14:49.680
corresponding rational number we get. So, we can&nbsp;
evaluate rational poly numbers at, say, integers.

00:14:49.680 --> 00:14:57.320
So, now that we're all happy with rational poly&nbsp;
numbers, let's use them to extend our notion of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:57.320 --> 00:15:04.400
on sequences to consider more general infinite&nbsp;
sequences. We're replacing the term "infinite&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:04.400 --> 00:15:11.240
sequences" with "on sequences," short for "ongoing&nbsp;
sequences." So, the idea is we're going to start&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:11.240 --> 00:15:17.560
with a rational poly number, and we're going&nbsp;
to generate a sequence from it. We'll call&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:17.560 --> 00:15:24.320
that a rational polyon sequence, and here's our&nbsp;
notation. It's already familiar by now, I hope:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:24.320 --> 00:15:32.280
left square bracket, the actual rational poly&nbsp;
number, and then a right-pointed bracket. An&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:32.280 --> 00:15:40.320
alternate notation is we're going to replace the&nbsp;
alpha in P with the letter n. N is our favorite&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:40.320 --> 00:15:50.200
number for sequences, and that expression will&nbsp;
also indicate to us that we have a sequence here.

00:15:50.200 --> 00:15:57.400
And the crucial thing about a sequence, or an on&nbsp;
sequence, is that we can pick out the K element,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:57.400 --> 00:16:07.760
where K is usually a natural number for us—so 1,&nbsp;
2, 3, 4, and so on. And the definition is that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:07.760 --> 00:16:15.560
if we take this rational poly number P and then&nbsp;
generate this on sequence, then the K element&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:15.560 --> 00:16:24.640
in that on sequence is, by definition, P of K.&nbsp;
Now, that's in general a rational number, not an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:24.640 --> 00:16:32.280
integer—so K is an integer, but what's on this&nbsp;
side here will typically be a rational number.

00:16:32.280 --> 00:16:39.360
So, let us look at an example. Here&nbsp;
is our rational poly number P: it is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:39.360 --> 00:16:48.760
1 + Alpha - Alpha squared over 2 + Alpha cubed.&nbsp;
So, one integral polynomial in the numerator,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:48.760 --> 00:16:57.960
another integral polynomial in the denominator.&nbsp;
Then what is the corresponding on sequence? We&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:57.960 --> 00:17:04.440
can write it as the sequence P, or to be more&nbsp;
explicit, we can write it this way, with this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:04.440 --> 00:17:12.920
expression put in here, the alphas replaced with&nbsp;
n's. So, the sequence 1 + n - n^2 over 2 + n^3.

00:17:15.280 --> 00:17:21.040
Okay, and what is this sequence?&nbsp;
It's the sequence that you get&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:21.040 --> 00:17:28.400
by starting to calculate the values of&nbsp;
this thing—first when n is equal to one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:28.400 --> 00:17:34.840
then when n is equal to two, then when n is&nbsp;
equal to three, and so on. So, for example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:34.840 --> 00:17:42.280
when n is equal to one, we get 1 + 1 - 1^2—that's&nbsp;
a total of one on the top—over 2 + 1^3,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:42.280 --> 00:17:53.440
that's 3. If n is equal to 2, we would have 1 +&nbsp;
2 - 4, that's minus 1 altogether, over 2 + 2^3,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:54.360 --> 00:18:08.720
which is 10. So that should be -1/10. And the next&nbsp;
one, let's just check that: if n is equal to 3,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:08.720 --> 00:18:20.200
1 + 3 - 9, that's 4 - 9, that's -5, over 2&nbsp;
+ 3^3, that's 2 + 27, that is in fact 29.

00:18:20.200 --> 00:18:27.240
Alright, so if our arithmetic is good, we&nbsp;
can carry on generating more and more terms,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:27.240 --> 00:18:30.360
and of course the thing doesn't&nbsp;
necessarily stop—it sort of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:30.360 --> 00:18:35.280
keeps on going. Depending on how much&nbsp;
patience and computing power we have,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:35.280 --> 00:18:43.720
we can keep on generating more and&nbsp;
more terms in this ongoing sequence.

00:18:43.720 --> 00:18:50.920
So, now we've extended our notion of infinite&nbsp;
sequences, or on sequences, in an important way.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:50.920 --> 00:18:57.880
We've gone from constant on sequences to poly&nbsp;
number on sequences, and now to rational poly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:57.880 --> 00:19:04.680
number on sequences. So, these are now much more&nbsp;
general kinds of on sequences, and they're very&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:04.680 --> 00:19:14.880
important for us in calculus, as we'll see. These&nbsp;
are very much sort of workhorses of calculus.

00:19:14.880 --> 00:19:25.040
So, it all seems very good, but in fact there is&nbsp;
a big logical problem. What I've told you in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:25.040 --> 00:19:35.240
last few slides is logically weak. There is&nbsp;
a key problem that I have sloughed over and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:35.240 --> 00:19:42.560
not mentioned, and I wonder how many of you have&nbsp;
caught on to what that is. So, it's now a great&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:42.560 --> 00:19:49.240
exercise to go over these few pages and to look&nbsp;
very carefully at what I've done and ask yourself,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:49.240 --> 00:19:55.400
okay, what is the problem here? There's&nbsp;
a logical problem. So, you might want to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:55.400 --> 00:20:03.760
stop the video and go over these issues, have a&nbsp;
look, spend perhaps some days thinking about it.

00:20:03.760 --> 00:20:09.040
Okay, there's a logical problem, and you want&nbsp;
to find out what it is. It's not particularly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:09.040 --> 00:20:14.800
subtle—it's pretty straightforward, and once&nbsp;
you see it, it's kind of obvious, right? So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:14.800 --> 00:20:22.880
please have a look and have a think about what is&nbsp;
the logical problem that I've been ignoring here.

00:20:22.880 --> 00:20:27.520
So, I hope you found what that logical&nbsp;
problem is yourselves. Okay, and it comes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:27.520 --> 00:20:34.520
down to a very common source of difficulty&nbsp;
in mathematics—elementary but common—which is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:34.520 --> 00:20:42.040
that division by zero is illegal. That's the one&nbsp;
operation with rational numbers that we are not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:42.040 --> 00:20:51.200
allowed to do. And unfortunately, we have built&nbsp;
in the possibility of division by zero so far&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:51.200 --> 00:21:00.440
in our treatment of these rational poly number&nbsp;
on sequences. For example, suppose that we had&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:00.440 --> 00:21:08.040
looked at the rational poly number Alpha over 2&nbsp;
- Alpha. This is a rational poly number because&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:08.040 --> 00:21:15.800
it's an integral poly number over another integral&nbsp;
poly number. Okay, here's the associated rational&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:15.800 --> 00:21:24.600
polyon sequence: n over 2 - n. What's the sequence&nbsp;
associated with it? Well, we just start generating&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:24.600 --> 00:21:34.800
values—when n is 1, we get 1 over 2 - 1, that's&nbsp;
1 over 1. When n is 2, we get 2 over 2 - 2, that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:34.800 --> 00:21:46.360
unfortunately is 2 over 0. When n is 3, we get 3&nbsp;
over 2 - 3, that's 3 over -1. My arithmetic is not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:46.360 --> 00:21:54.440
very good today. There we go. And we could keep&nbsp;
on going, and there would be no more problems.

00:21:54.440 --> 00:21:58.160
However, there's no escaping the&nbsp;
fact that when n is equal to 2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:58.160 --> 00:22:06.200
we have forced ourselves to make an&nbsp;
illegal operation—2 over 0. All bets are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:06.200 --> 00:22:14.520
off. This object collapses as a logically&nbsp;
coherent thing. It just does not work.

00:22:14.520 --> 00:22:19.480
Let's look at another example, slightly&nbsp;
more complicated. Here we have a rational&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:19.480 --> 00:22:27.800
poly number Q: 1 over 3 - 4 Alpha - 2&nbsp;
Alpha squared + Alpha cubed. Alright,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:27.800 --> 00:22:39.160
so we can generate values. When you plug in Alpha&nbsp;
= 1, then you get 3 - 4 - 2 + 1, that's 4 - 6,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:39.160 --> 00:22:47.280
that'd be minus 2, so we get -1/2. When n is 2,&nbsp;
hopefully it'll be minus 1/5. And what happens&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:47.280 --> 00:22:54.720
when n is equal to 3? Well, it's not so obvious&nbsp;
here, but let's have a look: 3 - 12, and then&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:54.720 --> 00:23:04.840
this will be -18 + 27. So altogether, 3 + 27,&nbsp;
that's 30, and -2 - 18, that's -30. We're going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:04.840 --> 00:23:17.960
to get zero in the denominator again. This just&nbsp;
does not work. This is not a legitimate object.

00:23:17.960 --> 00:23:26.080
So that's certainly a problem, but there's another&nbsp;
kind of problem also—a more subtle kind of problem&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:26.080 --> 00:23:33.360
but just as important. Consider the following&nbsp;
example, which seems to be quite okay: the example&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:33.360 --> 00:23:41.280
R = Alpha over 1 + Alpha. The associated&nbsp;
on sequence n over 1 + n. This is clearly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:41.280 --> 00:24:05.960
unsurprising. This same poly number R is also&nbsp;
equal to this poly number—these are exactly the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:05.960 --> 00:24:14.560
same poly numbers. The numerator here is obtained&nbsp;
from this one by multiplying by 1 - Alpha. The&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:14.560 --> 00:24:20.160
denominator here is obtained from this one by&nbsp;
multiplying by 1 - Alpha. Since we're multiplying&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:20.160 --> 00:24:25.240
by the same things top and bottom, there's&nbsp;
no question that this object and this object&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:25.240 --> 00:24:31.880
are exactly the same. We've agreed that they're&nbsp;
exactly the same poly numbers, exactly the same&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:31.880 --> 00:24:41.320
rational poly numbers. The associated on sequence&nbsp;
we ought to write like this: n - n^2 over 1 - n^2.

00:24:41.320 --> 00:24:48.600
So, what is the associated sequence? Well, when&nbsp;
we evaluate this thing when n is equal to 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:48.600 --> 00:24:56.360
the rule is to plug n = 1 into the numerator. We&nbsp;
get 0. Plug n into the denominator, we get 1 - 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:56.360 --> 00:25:08.920
another 0. We're getting 0 over 0, which is also&nbsp;
undefined. Subsequent values are okay—2/3, 3/4,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:08.920 --> 00:25:15.240
and so on. So, these two sequences&nbsp;
agree perfectly, except at the first&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:15.240 --> 00:25:21.400
term. There's a difference: this one was&nbsp;
well-defined, this one was not well-defined,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:21.400 --> 00:25:27.360
yet we said that these were actually going&nbsp;
to be the same rational poly numbers.

00:25:27.360 --> 00:25:38.360
So, we have a problem here: the evaluation of a&nbsp;
rational poly number is not well defined. We were&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:38.360 --> 00:25:45.960
too hasty, a little bit too simple-minded,&nbsp;
in assigning a meaning to the evaluation&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:45.960 --> 00:25:54.360
of a rational poly number. So, we have to go&nbsp;
back and rethink that important definition.

00:25:54.360 --> 00:25:59.480
Let's have a closer look at one&nbsp;
of the offending examples. Here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:59.480 --> 00:26:05.880
these two expressions as rational poly numbers&nbsp;
are equal. This is the example we had on the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:05.880 --> 00:26:12.000
last sheet—this one just obtained from this one by&nbsp;
multiplying the top and bottom by 1 - Alpha. Now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:12.000 --> 00:26:20.680
these two expressions agree at all&nbsp;
rational values except at 1. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:20.680 --> 00:26:25.240
when you take any rational value and plug it&nbsp;
into both of these things, you're going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:25.240 --> 00:26:33.440
get the same expression unless R is equal to 1.&nbsp;
When R is equal to 1, this will evaluate to 1/2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:35.000 --> 00:26:44.360
but this will evaluate to 0/0. The reason is that&nbsp;
the polynomial that we've multiplied this one by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:44.360 --> 00:26:52.880
to get this, which is 1 - Alpha over 1 - Alpha,&nbsp;
evaluates to 1 for every rational value except&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:52.880 --> 00:27:01.320
r = 1. In other words, this has the value 1 if&nbsp;
you replace Alpha with any number whatsoever—so&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:01.320 --> 00:27:13.160
obviously except when you replace Alpha with 1,&nbsp;
in which case you get 0/0, which is undefined.

00:27:13.160 --> 00:27:18.680
So, I think we can see the reason why things&nbsp;
are going wrong. These two expressions are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:18.680 --> 00:27:25.240
agreeing completely, except when R just has&nbsp;
this particular value of 1 because of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:25.240 --> 00:27:34.760
sort of artificial 0/0 that multiplying&nbsp;
by this term introduced. In particular,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:34.760 --> 00:27:43.160
if R is a rational number which is close to&nbsp;
1, close to 1 but not actually equal to 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:43.160 --> 00:27:55.320
like perhaps 0.998 or 1.3, then we know&nbsp;
that replacing this with r gives the same&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:55.320 --> 00:28:04.800
value—these things are actually equal. So, the two&nbsp;
expressions agree even for R very close to 1; it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:04.800 --> 00:28:15.040
just that exactly at 1 they happen to disagree&nbsp;
because of the 0/0 that's being introduced there.

00:28:15.040 --> 00:28:20.920
Alright, so let's go back to this issue of&nbsp;
evaluating a rational poly number, and let's be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:20.920 --> 00:28:29.080
a little bit more careful about this definition.&nbsp;
We'll suppose that P equals A/B, where A and B are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:29.080 --> 00:28:35.080
integral poly numbers, and we'll suppose that&nbsp;
K is an integer—or actually, for sequences,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:35.080 --> 00:28:44.520
just a natural number will do. The idea is we&nbsp;
want to evaluate P at this natural number K. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:44.520 --> 00:28:50.640
we're going to do two things: we're going to look&nbsp;
at the numerator A, and we're going to write it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:50.640 --> 00:28:59.840
by factoring out Alpha - K. Perhaps Alpha - K is&nbsp;
a factor of this polynomial—this is an integral&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:59.840 --> 00:29:06.520
polynomial, so maybe it has Alpha - K as a factor,&nbsp;
maybe it has Alpha - K squared as a factor, or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:06.520 --> 00:29:15.800
Alpha - K cubed. We're going to factor out as many&nbsp;
of these Alpha - K's as we can and write A as a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:15.800 --> 00:29:25.120
product of some other sort of quotient polynomial,&nbsp;
Alpha tilde, say, times this term Alpha - K to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:25.120 --> 00:29:32.880
the power of n. The crucial thing about this is&nbsp;
that it does not have Alpha - K as a factor. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:32.880 --> 00:29:41.040
by Descartes' factor theorem, if it doesn't have&nbsp;
Alpha - K as a factor, it means that when we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:41.040 --> 00:29:50.880
evaluate it at K, we're not getting zero. Now, it&nbsp;
might be that this n is actually zero, so it might&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:50.880 --> 00:30:01.080
be that A doesn't have any factors of Alpha - K.&nbsp;
That's okay, so we include that possibility, where&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:01.080 --> 00:30:11.800
n is zero. We do the same thing for B: we write&nbsp;
it as some polynomial B hat times some power Alpha&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:11.800 --> 00:30:20.240
- K to the power of m, say, where again, this&nbsp;
polynomial B hat has the property that when you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:20.240 --> 00:30:28.440
evaluate it at K, you don't get zero. So here, n&nbsp;
and m are natural numbers augmented with zero, so&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:28.440 --> 00:30:37.000
we're including all natural numbers—1, 2, 3, and&nbsp;
also the possibility that the exponents are zero.

00:30:37.000 --> 00:30:44.200
So, this is a preliminary to defining&nbsp;
what P of K is. Having done this,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:44.200 --> 00:30:51.680
we are now in a position to define P of&nbsp;
K, and here's the definition. It might&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:51.680 --> 00:30:58.040
look a little bit surprising; there's some new&nbsp;
things involved here. Alright, first of all,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:58.040 --> 00:31:04.440
there are three different cases depending on&nbsp;
the relationship between these numbers n and m:

00:31:04.440 --> 00:31:10.400
If n is bigger than m—in other words,&nbsp;
if there are more factors of Alpha - K&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:10.400 --> 00:31:19.320
in the numerator than there are in the&nbsp;
denominator—then we define P of K to be zero.&nbsp;

00:31:19.320 --> 00:31:24.760
If they're exactly equal, if there's the same&nbsp;
number of Alpha - K's in the numerator and in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:24.760 --> 00:31:36.080
denominator, then we define P of K to be Alpha hat&nbsp;
of K over B hat of K. In other words, we just look&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:36.080 --> 00:31:43.040
at this thing over this thing—essentially, we're&nbsp;
canceling out the Alpha - K to the power of n&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:43.040 --> 00:31:47.760
and the Alpha - K to the power of m, top&nbsp;
and bottom, because the exponents are the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:47.760 --> 00:31:54.240
same in this case. The crucial thing is these&nbsp;
are nonzero numbers, because by assumption,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:54.240 --> 00:32:02.280
this is nonzero, and this is also nonzero, so&nbsp;
this rational number actually does make sense.&nbsp;

00:32:02.280 --> 00:32:08.640
But there's a third case, the case&nbsp;
when n is less than m—in other words,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:08.640 --> 00:32:16.400
where there are more factors of Alpha - K in the&nbsp;
denominator than in the numerator. In that case,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:16.400 --> 00:32:28.480
we are going to define P of K to be infinity.
Wait a minute, what does that mean? Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:28.480 --> 00:32:36.360
this sideways eight is a new symbol that we're&nbsp;
introducing. It's just a new symbol. Its name&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:36.360 --> 00:32:43.640
is rather grandiosely "infinity"—that's what&nbsp;
we're going to call this sideways eight. You&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:43.640 --> 00:32:47.840
can just think of it as something that&nbsp;
we draw on the paper; it looks pretty,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:47.840 --> 00:32:56.520
it's like a lemniscate. And we're going to agree&nbsp;
that if this exponent is less than this exponent,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:56.520 --> 00:33:03.800
then P of K is infinity. Admittedly, this is&nbsp;
not a rational number—right? It's definitely&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:03.800 --> 00:33:11.760
not a rational number; it's a new expression&nbsp;
that is outside our current number system.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:11.760 --> 00:33:15.800
And it's just one of the realities&nbsp;
of mathematics that at some point,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:15.800 --> 00:33:23.200
it's necessary to think about extending&nbsp;
our number system to include a number&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:23.200 --> 00:33:30.160
that plays the role—or an object that plays the&nbsp;
role—of infinity. That's what we're doing now.

00:33:30.160 --> 00:33:34.920
So, we're going to talk more about this—this is&nbsp;
a very interesting development. But basically,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:34.920 --> 00:33:40.560
we have no choice; we have to do this&nbsp;
if we want to have a sort of consistent&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:40.560 --> 00:33:48.040
understanding of the sequences&nbsp;
generated by rational poly numbers.

00:33:48.040 --> 00:33:52.520
Okay, so this is a very important&nbsp;
definition. It probably requires a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:52.520 --> 00:33:56.560
few hours of thinking about—right? Write&nbsp;
out this definition, stare at it. Now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:56.560 --> 00:34:01.800
let's have a look at some examples—always&nbsp;
the best way to understand and to start to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:01.800 --> 00:34:09.520
appreciate what the definition actually means.&nbsp;
Okay, without examples, this is all sterile.

00:34:09.520 --> 00:34:15.880
Alright, so let's look at an example. Here is&nbsp;
the polynomial P = Alpha - Alpha squared over&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:15.880 --> 00:34:23.240
1 - Alpha squared. Let's think about evaluating&nbsp;
it at the number one. It's obviously going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:23.240 --> 00:34:28.320
be problematic because in the numerator, we have&nbsp;
1 - 1, which is zero, and in the denominator, we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:28.320 --> 00:34:36.160
also have 1 - 1, which is zero. So, what we have&nbsp;
to do is factor the numerator and the denominator,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:36.160 --> 00:34:42.560
and we're particularly interested in factors of&nbsp;
the form Alpha - 1. Okay, in this case, it's a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:42.560 --> 00:34:46.960
little bit easier if we use 1 - Alpha, because&nbsp;
the arithmetic is just a little bit easier. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:46.960 --> 00:34:54.120
I'm going to factor a 1 - Alpha out there and a&nbsp;
1 - Alpha out there. 1 - Alpha over 1 - Alpha,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:54.120 --> 00:35:03.720
it's the same as Alpha - 1 over Alpha - 1.&nbsp;
Alright, so having done that, we see that this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:03.720 --> 00:35:10.760
thing really is the same as Alpha over 1 + Alpha.&nbsp;
So, 1 - Alpha appears with an exponent of one in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:10.760 --> 00:35:19.280
the numerator and also one in the denominator.&nbsp;
That's that middle case. The middle case means&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:19.280 --> 00:35:25.320
that we basically factor these things out, we&nbsp;
disregard them, and just consider the rest,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:25.320 --> 00:35:32.920
which is Alpha over 1 + Alpha, and plug 1&nbsp;
into that. So, this is the A hat, and this is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:32.920 --> 00:35:47.560
the B hat in the former notation. So, we just&nbsp;
plug Alpha = 1 here and here to get 1 over 2.

00:35:47.560 --> 00:35:56.280
And okay, we can think about also roughly a kind&nbsp;
of a limit that, if we look at this expression&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:56.280 --> 00:36:05.760
here or we look at this expression here, if R is&nbsp;
a number, a rational number, that's approaching 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:05.760 --> 00:36:10.600
then the value of this thing is going to be&nbsp;
the same thing as the value of this thing,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:10.600 --> 00:36:16.440
as long as R is not equal to 1. And then, as&nbsp;
the value approaches 1, well, this is going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:16.440 --> 00:36:21.760
to approach 1/2. So, another way of thinking&nbsp;
about what we're doing here is we're really&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:21.760 --> 00:36:30.000
sort of thinking about the limit as R approaches&nbsp;
1 of P of R. But we haven't defined limits yet,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:30.000 --> 00:36:35.840
so this is just a rather informal observation&nbsp;
that what we're doing here is a kind of an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:35.840 --> 00:36:45.360
algebraic equivalent of taking a limit, for&nbsp;
those of you who have had some calculus before.

00:36:45.360 --> 00:36:53.840
Alright, so now we're in a position to write down&nbsp;
the on sequence for this rational polyon sequence.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:53.840 --> 00:37:06.240
The value at 1 is not 0/0—the value at 1 is 1/2,&nbsp;
as we've just computed. The value at 2 is 2/3,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:06.240 --> 00:37:17.040
then at 3, 3/4, then 4/5, and so on. So, it&nbsp;
gives us a completely legitimate on sequence,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:17.040 --> 00:37:26.080
even though at first glance you might say&nbsp;
this is undefined when n is equal to 1.

00:37:26.080 --> 00:37:32.080
So, those of you who are used to calculus and&nbsp;
treating functions in calculus, there's some&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:32.080 --> 00:37:39.600
adjustment to be made here. We are not thinking&nbsp;
about this thing as primarily a function—that is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:39.600 --> 00:37:46.200
not what it is. It's a rational poly number,&nbsp;
and as a rational poly number, this thing and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:46.200 --> 00:37:54.640
this thing are exactly equal. In calculus, if you&nbsp;
were thinking of these as functions in calculus,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:54.640 --> 00:37:59.200
you would have to say that as functions,&nbsp;
these were almost equal, but not quite equal,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:59.200 --> 00:38:05.120
because their values at 1 were not the same.&nbsp;
We are not adopting that point of view. These&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:05.120 --> 00:38:10.760
are exactly the same objects for us, and so&nbsp;
the on sequences that they generate have to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:10.760 --> 00:38:18.720
be exactly the same. And so, we are forced&nbsp;
to introduce our evaluation as we've done to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:18.720 --> 00:38:25.560
talk consistently about the on sequence&nbsp;
associated with a rational poly number.

00:38:25.560 --> 00:38:29.720
Let's look at another example, a&nbsp;
bit more complicated. Here we have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:29.720 --> 00:38:40.000
P = 6 - 5 Alpha + Alpha squared over -6 + 20&nbsp;
Alpha - 8 Alpha squared + Alpha cubed. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:40.000 --> 00:38:45.680
if you set Alpha equal to 1 in here, it's not&nbsp;
too hard to see you're going to get 2 over -3,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:45.680 --> 00:38:56.360
or -2/3. If you plug 2 in, well, you're going&nbsp;
to get 6 - 10 + 4, that's zero on the top,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:56.360 --> 00:39:11.320
and in the bottom here, you're going to get -6&nbsp;
+ 20 - 32 + 8, which is also zero. And well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:11.320 --> 00:39:18.240
these other values are made a little bit simpler&nbsp;
by realizing that the polynomials that are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:18.240 --> 00:39:25.320
involved here can be factored. So, the numerator&nbsp;
can be factored as Alpha - 3 times Alpha - 2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:25.320 --> 00:39:33.560
and this denominator can be factored as Alpha - 4&nbsp;
times Alpha - 2 squared. So, that makes it clear&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:33.560 --> 00:39:41.800
what's going to happen when we plug in Alpha =&nbsp;
2: we're going to get 0/0 because of these terms&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:41.800 --> 00:39:48.120
here, at least when we have the naive approach.&nbsp;
But now, with our more sophisticated notion of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:48.120 --> 00:39:55.680
evaluation, we know that that's not quite what&nbsp;
we're going to get. To evaluate this thing at 2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:55.680 --> 00:40:00.520
what we need to do is we need to look at these&nbsp;
factors of Alpha - 2 that are appearing in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:00.520 --> 00:40:06.360
numerator and denominator, and notice that&nbsp;
the exponent in the denominator is bigger&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:06.360 --> 00:40:13.920
than the exponent in the numerator—there's more&nbsp;
Alpha - 2's in the denominator than there is in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:13.920 --> 00:40:23.920
the numerator. That means that our definition&nbsp;
is that P of 2 is our new symbol, infinity.

00:40:23.920 --> 00:40:29.840
How about evaluating it at 3? Well, this form of&nbsp;
it makes it kind of obvious that the numerator&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:29.840 --> 00:40:33.880
is going to be zero, and the denominator is&nbsp;
going to be nonzero, so we're going to get&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:33.880 --> 00:40:43.440
zero as the quotient. And when Alpha is equal to&nbsp;
4, or when n is equal to 4, we get a zero in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:43.440 --> 00:40:52.040
denominator here and no Alpha - 4 term in the&nbsp;
numerator. So again, that's the third case—we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:52.040 --> 00:41:01.240
must put in infinity. Then at 5, we're out of the&nbsp;
woods—then we have 5 - 3, which is 2 times 5 - 2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:01.240 --> 00:41:12.760
which is 3, over 5 - 4, which is 1, times 5 - 2,&nbsp;
that's 3 squared. So that'll be 6/9, which is 2/3.

00:41:12.760 --> 00:41:25.840
So, the associated on sequence to this&nbsp;
poly number is -2/3, and then infinity,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:25.840 --> 00:41:31.040
and then zero, and then another&nbsp;
infinity, and then 2/3, and then,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:31.040 --> 00:41:38.560
well, we could evaluate some more just&nbsp;
by substituting in here and evaluating.

00:41:38.560 --> 00:41:46.480
So, we necessarily get on sequences whose&nbsp;
entries are not just rational numbers, but&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:46.480 --> 00:41:54.480
also involve this new object—maybe we shouldn't&nbsp;
call it a number yet; it's a new expression,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:54.480 --> 00:42:02.200
this sideways 8, which we're calling infinity,&nbsp;
rather grandiosely. Probably it would be better&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:42:02.200 --> 00:42:07.040
if we called it something else, but there's no way&nbsp;
to change the established convention with regard&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:42:07.040 --> 00:42:13.200
to this symbol. We have to call it infinity,&nbsp;
and it's actually not such a bad idea anyway,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:42:13.200 --> 00:42:21.360
as we'll now see by actually looking at&nbsp;
a picture of these rational poly numbers.

00:42:21.360 --> 00:42:29.520
So, we've spent a little bit of time graphing&nbsp;
poly numbers or polynomials. The idea with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:42:29.520 --> 00:42:34.480
rational poly numbers is much the same, except&nbsp;
that it's a little bit more complicated,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:42:34.480 --> 00:42:42.800
and we have to be prepared to use rational&nbsp;
numbers. Here's our first example of the rational&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:42:42.800 --> 00:42:48.040
polynomial Alpha - Alpha squared over 1 - Alpha&nbsp;
squared, and I'm writing it here sort of more in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:42:48.040 --> 00:42:56.160
calculus style with an x and a y, reflecting&nbsp;
our x and y graphs that we like to draw.

00:42:56.760 --> 00:43:02.040
So, how do we come up with a plot like this? Well,&nbsp;
it's exactly the same kind of thing that you do&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:43:02.040 --> 00:43:12.240
before: you plug in various values of x, say x =&nbsp;
2, that would give us 2 - 4, that'd be minus 2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:43:12.240 --> 00:43:19.720
over 1 - 4, that'd be minus 3. So, -2 over -3,&nbsp;
that'd be 2/3. So, I have to go up to the 2/3&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:43:19.720 --> 00:43:25.360
level, and I would mark a point there. So, if&nbsp;
you calculate lots of points and then you just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:43:25.360 --> 00:43:33.800
connect them with little lines, then you get this&nbsp;
graph that looks partially like this. Of course,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:43:33.800 --> 00:43:40.200
this is just part of the picture; there's more&nbsp;
outside, and of course, as we become more and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:43:40.200 --> 00:43:49.200
more refined, this is just my very rough&nbsp;
drawing of this thing, not very accurate.

00:43:49.200 --> 00:43:54.800
The associated on sequence is just obtained&nbsp;
when we restrict ourselves to the values 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:43:54.800 --> 00:44:03.200
2, 3, and 4, and so on. So,&nbsp;
the value at 1 is a half,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:44:03.200 --> 00:44:09.560
the value at 2 is 2/3, the&nbsp;
value at 3 is 3/4, and so on.

00:44:09.560 --> 00:44:14.760
There's a few things to notice about this graph,&nbsp;
of course. There's something special happening at&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:44:14.760 --> 00:44:25.240
x = -1 and at x = 1, because the denominator is&nbsp;
zero at both of those. The value at x = 1 turns&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:44:25.240 --> 00:44:31.000
out to be sort of an optical illusion because&nbsp;
of the common factor of 1 - x in the numerator&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:44:31.000 --> 00:44:40.200
and denominator. But at x = -1, we have a&nbsp;
more crucial kind of singularity here. The&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:44:40.200 --> 00:44:46.680
graph really does kind of go further and further&nbsp;
down as we approach minus one from the right,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:44:46.680 --> 00:44:54.240
and here, as we approach minus one from&nbsp;
the left, it goes up and up and up. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:44:54.240 --> 00:45:04.280
it would be quite correct to say that the&nbsp;
value of this thing at minus one is infinity.

00:45:04.280 --> 00:45:11.000
What about this one here? That was our second&nbsp;
example: x - 3 times x - 2 over x - 4 times x - 2&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:45:11.000 --> 00:45:18.080
squared. Well, that's a little bit more&nbsp;
complicated. There's now a singularity at 2 and 4,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:45:18.080 --> 00:45:26.840
corresponding to the two factors x - 4 and x -&nbsp;
2 in the denominator. The graph looks something&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:45:26.840 --> 00:45:37.560
like this, and this goes off to zero. So, we're&nbsp;
going to talk more about graphs of rational poly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:45:37.560 --> 00:45:43.880
numbers like this. I don't expect you to be able&nbsp;
to graph these so easily on your own—we'll talk a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:45:43.880 --> 00:45:48.400
little bit more about these. These are going&nbsp;
to play a very important role in calculus;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:45:48.400 --> 00:45:53.640
these are very, very important objects.&nbsp;
This is just an introduction to them.

00:45:53.640 --> 00:45:59.560
And here's the sequence that we get by looking&nbsp;
at the values at 1, at 2, at 3, at 4, and 5,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:45:59.560 --> 00:46:08.760
and so on. At 1, we decided we had -2/3. At 2, we&nbsp;
had infinity—that was our sideways eight. At 3,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:46:08.760 --> 00:46:13.240
we have zero—you can see it going through&nbsp;
zero there. At 4, you can see again the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:46:13.240 --> 00:46:24.840
infinite aspect of it. At 5, it becomes 2/3,&nbsp;
and then it decreases from that on toward zero.

00:46:24.840 --> 00:46:29.800
So, these infinities that are appearing&nbsp;
here, of course, are very interesting,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:46:29.800 --> 00:46:37.320
and they're reflecting the fact that the graphs of&nbsp;
these functions are doing something interesting at&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:46:37.320 --> 00:46:45.160
these values—at 2 and 4 here, and at minus 1&nbsp;
here. The limit of the values really is—well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:46:45.160 --> 00:46:50.160
it's going sort of down, down, down, sort&nbsp;
of towards minus infinity, you might say.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:46:50.160 --> 00:46:56.840
And when we approach 2 from this side, it's&nbsp;
going up, up, up towards plus infinity. Maybe&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:46:56.840 --> 00:47:02.240
even in some sense, the values kind of agree&nbsp;
that maybe the infinite in this direction&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:47:02.240 --> 00:47:11.400
and the infinite in that direction somehow&nbsp;
meet—that's what the notation is suggesting.

00:47:11.400 --> 00:47:17.200
Okay, so we've opened up a new can of worms here.&nbsp;
We've opened up the possibility of extending our&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:47:17.200 --> 00:47:24.360
number system to include infinity. And you&nbsp;
may know that I don't like infinite sets,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:47:24.360 --> 00:47:29.840
okay, and I'm very modest about things like&nbsp;
this. So, we are not proposing that we are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:47:29.840 --> 00:47:35.920
now at the level of gods, okay, that we are&nbsp;
now somehow superior to what we were yesterday&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:47:35.920 --> 00:47:41.160
because we've introduced this symbol. No, it's&nbsp;
just a symbol—it's an expression that we write&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:47:41.160 --> 00:47:48.640
down on the paper, which has a very specific and&nbsp;
well-defined and coherent mathematical meaning.

00:47:48.640 --> 00:47:53.080
Next time, we're going to talk a little bit&nbsp;
more about the possible arithmetic that we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:47:53.080 --> 00:48:01.640
might get by extending our favorite rational&nbsp;
number system to include this new expression,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:48:01.640 --> 00:48:09.480
infinity. Is it possible? Does it work? It's&nbsp;
a favorite subject of amateur mathematicians,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:48:09.480 --> 00:48:13.520
so we're going to go down a little&nbsp;
bit of that track next time. I hope&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:48:13.520 --> 00:48:25.640
you'll join me for that. I'm Norman&nbsp;
Wildberger—thanks for listening.

00:48:25.640 --> 00:48:26.640
[Music]

